it is very common to factor out non-trivial components into inner classes. for example, ShoppingCartPage might have BuyButton, ClearAllButton, UpdateButton, etc as inner non-static classes. depending on how big they are sometimes its easier to inject dependencies directly into them because its easier to track when looking at code. sometimes buttons need dependencies that only they use, so it again makes sense to inject the button directly. yet, other times it actually makes a difference which class you inject:

```
public class CartPage extends WebPage {
   class BuyButton extends Button {

      @Inject Logger logger; 

      onSubmit() {
       // do submit stuff
       logger.info("..");
      }
  }
}
```

i want the logger to use the BuyButton class name as the category instead of the CartPage so i have to inject it into BuyButton.

anyways, it is very common to have a lot of complex anonymous and inner classes as wicket components - after all thats the point of wicket.

-1 on the enable/disable part.

